# 🔬 PS2: Academic Integrity Analyzer — Complete Execution Blueprint

> **Selected Problem Statement**: PS2 — Academic Integrity Analyzer  
> **Track**: Others (Open Track)  
> **Team Size**: 5 Members  
> **Duration**: 24 hours  
> **Key Asset**: OpenAI API Key (GPT-4 + Embeddings)

---

## 📋 Problem Statement — Sentence-by-Sentence Decomposition

Every verb = a feature. Every noun = a data model. Every adjective = a validation rule.

### Problem Context
> *"Academic plagiarism has evolved beyond direct copying. A growing pattern involves students composing submissions by splicing sections from multiple existing papers, creating a superficially original document that evades traditional plagiarism detection tools. These composite papers are difficult to catch because no single section is copied verbatim — the fraud lies in the assembly."*

**Key insight for judges**: This isn't regular plagiarism detection (Turnitin). This is **stitched authorship detection** — multiple writing styles assembled into one document. Our system catches what existing tools miss.

### Required Deliverable
> *"Build a system that detects this form of academic dishonesty through **stylometric analysis**, **citation forensics**, and **semantic source tracing**."*

**Three pillars** — every feature maps to one of these. All three MUST be present:

| Pillar | What It Means | Priority |
|--------|--------------|----------|
| 🔴 **Stylometric Analysis** | Detect different writing styles across paragraphs | P0 — Core |
| 🔴 **Citation Forensics** | Analyze reference patterns for inconsistencies | P0 — Core |
| 🟡 **Semantic Source Tracing** | Find probable source papers for flagged sections | P1 — Important |

---

## ✅ Complete Requirement Extraction

Every single deliverable pulled from the problem statement, with priority:

| # | Requirement (Exact from PS) | Pillar | Priority | Complexity |
|---|---------------------------|--------|----------|-----------|
| **F1** | **Ingest a research paper PDF** | Input | 🔴 P0 | Low |
| **F2** | **Produce a structured forensic report** | Output | 🔴 P0 | Medium |
| **F3** | **Extract and segment the paper by paragraph** | Processing | 🔴 P0 | Low |
| **F4** | **Writing style analysis across sections** — identify shifts in voice, vocabulary distribution, sentence structure, linguistic fingerprint | Stylometry | 🔴 P0 | High |
| **F5** | **Flag sections with distinct stylometric profiles** as potentially authored by different individuals | Stylometry | 🔴 P0 | Medium |
| **F6** | **Citation graph analysis** — examine whether reference clusters are temporally or thematically inconsistent across sections | Citation | 🔴 P0 | Medium |
| **F7** | **Estimate the minimum number of distinct authors** present in the document | Stylometry | 🔴 P0 | Medium |
| **F8** | **Paragraph-level authorship heatmap** — visually mapping each section to its inferred style cluster | Visualization | 🔴 P0 | Medium |
| **F9** | **Cross-reference flagged sections against arxiv and IEEE** via semantic search | Source Tracing | 🟡 P1 | High |
| **F10** | **Surface probable source papers** with traceable evidence | Source Tracing | 🟡 P1 | High |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **F1–F8 are mandatory for 80% correctness score.** F9–F10 are for 20% completeness. Prioritize accordingly.

